@15:00.... it's not "wisdom."  Wisdom is the confluence of knowledge, experience, and good judgement.  What these LLMs facilitate is knowledge management, which captures a bit of a shadow of experience (the experience of the people who put the texts together), but their weakest link is that they really have no judgement at all.  Through various monitoring and grounding add-ons OpenAI and other researchers may be scratching the surface on imagining how to give these LLMs some kind of judgement, but we're a long way from being able to do that, particularly because of the LLM's lack of real experience.  In a way RLHF is the first step toward providing experience, but it's a vary narrowly defined kind of experience.

Experience is what tells you that the third time someone tries to ask you for help doing something illegal in a slightly different way that that person is nefarious, and you should dramatically reduce how willing you are to help them.  It's something we learn as children -- not everyone who acts nice or interested in you has your best interests in mind ("don't talk to strangers or don't take candy from strangers").  These grounding and monitoring approaches are a stopgap that's trying to mimic good judgement while skipping the experience step.  They're like hardcoding something into a program.  They can't really scale, and in order for AI to be safe, we actually need this good judgement characteristic to be intrinsic in the model itself (so you can't just skip it).  So there's a lot of work and research to be done here to figure out how to integrate these things so that an AI can begin the journey to becoming wise.  In some ways that's what makes this a really dangerous time.  We've invented the first algorithm that can loosely reason and comprehend knowledge, but has no intrinsic ethics.  Arguably it's the exact same problem we have with our own children each generation, but these LLMs aren't taught in the same way we teach children (over time, using experience, and encouraging the development of good judgement as an intrinsic part of their character).

The quest for wisdom in AI is going to take us into weird places too. For millennia humans have used religion as a way to collaborate on what ethics are. For maybe 200ish years we've been trying to separate ourselves from that approach of organizing ethics for many reasons: it is easily corruptible, it tends to be anecdotal and not comprehensive, it rarely provides strong guidance, and when it does sometimes it doesn't maximize utility, and so on. But we don't have any great alternatives, honestly. It's what Nietzsche worried about when he famously said "God is dead." Nietzsche wasn't celebrating it, he was lamenting it, because religion is easier. So will we resort to making AI religious as a stop gap? Seems like a really weird place to take something so advanced, doesn't it? But it may be a necessary step along the way, simply as a way to keep AI from being misused, and to give it a framework for collaborating with humans (and other AIs) on determining what good judgement looks like.
